[normal]Q2 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] I want to start with a few questions on the ONS quarter 
[normal]3
[normal] GDP statistics and, first of all, the construction sector.
[normal] 
[normal]Despite all the public good news on the economy, the current construction sector output is significantly below its 2011 level, even though the broader economy is growing.
[normal] 
[normal]Given the strategic significance of construction, do you think that economic growth and the construction sector’s role within it could be undermined by the construction sector’s lack of progress?
[normal]Vince [bold]Cable:[bold] It is certainly relatively weak, you are quite right.
[normal] 
[normal]The construction industry took a terrible pounding in recent years.
[normal] 
[normal]There was a combination of factors
[normal]:
[normal] the collapse of the housing market in the crisis and then commercial property and, 
[normal]particularly following the 2009 B
[normal]udget, very big cutbacks in capital spending, so the construction industry was very depressed.
[normal] 
[normal]There is some indication at the moment that there is recovery, but as you quite rightly point out, it is lagging behind the rest of the economy and in order to make its 
[normal]appropriate contribution we have to see, particularly, a signi
[normal]ficant upturn in house building—that is one of the key drivers—
[normal]together with progress on the big infrastructure projects.
[normal] 
[normal]The surveys, as opposed to the backward-looking indicators, do suggest that there is a much more positive spirit in that industry, but it has been through a torrid time and it still has not shown the level of recovery we 
[normal]would 
[normal]want.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q3 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] You have talked about housing; how reliant do you think the construction sector is on the Government’s home ownership and housing s
[normal]chemes, some of which you have
[normal] exercised some concern about?
[normal]Vince [bold]Cable:[bold] It is an important component.
[normal] T
[normal]he only thing I have said that is at all controversial is that you need to manage demand as well as boosting supply, but 
[normal]I think 
[normal]we can all agree on that
[normal]; i
[normal]t is just a question of how best you do it
[normal]. I
[normal]ndeed, the Bank of England and 
[normal]the 
[normal]Treasury have recognised that by changing the emphasis of the Funding for Lending Scheme so that it is now targeted at small business rather than at the mortgage market.
[normal] 
[normal]There is recognition that demand had to be managed and it is being managed.
[normal]I would just add one other thing on the construction industry.
[normal] 
[normal]We do recognise in BIS that quite apart from the big macroeconomic factors affecting construction
[normal],
[normal] there are some specific issues in relation to that industry that have been overlooked for very many years.
[normal] Construction is one of our 11 
[normal]sectors, because it is core to the economy.
[normal] 
[normal]When we have
[normal] got 
[normal]the industry round the table, as we have, we realise there are very, very deep issues regarding lack of skills, which come from a boom-bust cycle approach in parts of the industry
[normal], the lack of co-ordination. I
[normal]nnovation in the British construction industry is very weak compared with some other countries
[normal];
[normal] 
[normal]Scandinavia
[normal] has much more advanced building techniques.
[normal] 
[normal]We are trying to work with the industry on a long-term partnership basis, along with the rest of the industrial strategy to deal with those issues.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q4 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] You have par
[normal]tly pre-empted my next question. If I may, I shall
[normal] package a number of issues in just one question.
[normal] 
[normal]First of all, are you concerned that the industry seems over-reliant on housing schemes and, b
[normal]asically, what are you doing to
[normal] broaden the role that construction has and deal with the problems that are within it?
[normal]Vince [bold]Cable:[bold] Housing is a necessary part of the sector and indeed we want to see lots more houses being built, so if you mean over-reliance, it is not at the expense of housing supply.
[normal] 
[normal]We want to see a lot more houses built.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q5 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] I am talking about what steps you are tak
[normal]ing to improve construction in
[normal] the non-housing sector.
[normal] 
[normal]Nobody is saying that there should be any diminution.
[normal] 
[normal]Vince [bold]Cable:[bold] No, indeed.
[normal] 
[normal]The group we have now assembled around the construction industry is designed to address those bigger systemic, strategic issues.
[normal] As you know, Sir David 
[normal]Higgins’
[normal]s
[normal] track record is outstanding and he is chairing that group.
[normal] 
[normal]Part of what we are trying to do is to make sure that there is a long-term process in train for training.
[normal] 
[normal]One of the things that really worries us is that
[normal],
[normal] as the construction industry picks up from very low levels, it will immediately run into bottlenecks of skilled workers, many of whom disappeared from the labour market in the downturn.
[normal] 
[normal]We are trying to work with the 
[normal]industry to make sure that we have proper apprenticeship programmes, that they are identifying skill bottlenecks ahead and trying to identify other bottlenecks.
[normal] 
[normal]It is extraordinary that on some building sites I go to you find that they are having to import bricks
[normal],
[normal] because the kilns were closed down in the slump and they are now having to restore that capacity.
[normal] 
[normal]Therefore, to the extent to which we can in BIS with the limited instruments that we have, we want to try to help them deal with skill issues and other bottleneck problems.
[normal]Martin [bold]Donnelly:[bold] [bold]You may have seen the construction industrial strategy 
[normal]Construction 2025
[normal], which set out four high-
[normal]level ambitions for the next 11 
[normal]years
[normal]:[bold] to be cheaper, faster, have 50% lower emissions and improve our overall trade performance.
[normal] 
[normal]A delivery plan around that will be presented to the Industry Council next month, so that we are taking forward delivery of the strategy.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q6 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] We will monitor that carefully.
[normal] 
[normal]You mentioned, Minister, the
[normal] Funding for Lending Scheme, and quite rightly 
[normal]you said that demand was largely thro
[normal]ugh housing and needed to be re
[normal]focused on lending to small businesses.
[normal] 
[normal]Have
[normal] you any evidence that the take-
[normal]up from small businesses has improved since then?
[normal]Vince [bold]Cable:[bold] Not enormously.
[normal] 
[normal]As I understand it, the November figures are a bit better, but small business lending, as we have discussed many times in Committee, is very depressed.
[normal] 
[normal]It reflects the way in which the regulatory system bears upon the banks, the risk weights attached to SME lending, their general switch to more conservative policies.
[normal] 
[normal]If we look over the last few months, the net lending decline, which was apparent over 
[normal]a
[normal] long period of time, does appear to be bottoming out.
[normal] 
[normal]There is some evidence that it may be increasing and there are a lot of positive things happening that may not be fully captured in the statistics.
[normal] 
[normal]I am not sure, for example, that the peer-to-peer lending would be captured in the normal bank statistics.
[normal] 
[normal]Some of the other things we are financing and supporting, like invoice lending, asset-based funding, may not be captured in the numbers.
[normal] 
[normal]The sense we have is that the position is improving, but it is profoundly unsatisfactory.
[normal]&#xa0;
