[normal]Scotland
[normal] particularly, because although there are huge numbers of projects there, by their nature they tend to be smaller projects. Can anything be done to help them to be able to aggregate projects, to structure finance in a different way to be able to help that?
[normal]Vince Cable[bold]: 
[normal]I think they are very conscious. This is an institution using public money and the point I have made to them quite often is that we therefore want it to be publicly visible. 
[normal]We do not want to interfere, but we do want it to be publicly visible so that people in 
[normal]Scotland
[normal] and everywhere else can see where the money is going and identify with what is a very good and successful institution. 
[normal]The explanation for what you are describing is that when they are dealing with relatively small projects they tend to do it through funds, so there is a kind of aggregation of small projects in funds they support
[normal].
[normal] I have been round large numbers of openings, including a couple in 
[normal]Scotland
[normal], which have benefited directly from Green investment bank activity, but I hear what you say. This is a good institution, we helped to create it, it has good political support, but we must be able to demonstrate what is happening on the ground.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Chair:[bold] [bold]Obviously, we are now running into time for Prime Minister’s Questions. I understand, Minister, that you are okay to stay for some time; is that correct?
[normal]Vince Cable[bold]: 
[normal]Yes, if you wish me to
[normal].
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
